title: Production cross sections and the particle stability of proton-rich nuclei from Ni-58 fragmentation.

x4freetext: Production cross sections and the particle stability of
proton-rich nuclei from Ni-58 fragmentation.

x4codes.hlp: Centre d`Etudes Nucleaires de Bordeaux-Gradignan, France
GSI Helmholtzzent. f. Schwerionenforschung, Darmstadt, Germany

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.50, p.2398 (1994)

x4freetext: A beryllium-9 target, thickness 4 g/cm**2, was used.
/By authors/.Eight different settings of the fragment
separator have been used in order to select Ni-56,
because of a degrader thickness of only 1.5 g/cm**2 of
aluminum fragments between copper and scandium are
transmitted through the projectile-fragment separator
(FRS) Simultaneously and can be detected at the exit.
. A revised abrasion-ablation model and with the
statistical abrasion model.
Two position-sensitive plastic scintillators.
An ionization chamber (MUSIC) measured the
energy loss of the fragments in order to extact their
nuclear charge.

x4codes.hlp: GSI Helmholtzzent. f. Schwerionenforschung, Darmstadt, Germany

x4freetext: The counting rates of the different isotopes have to
be corrected for transmission losses in the
Spectrometer, for losses due to secondary interactions
in the target and in the intermediate degrader as well
as in the Detectors, for the dead time of the data
acquisition and for the Detector efficiencies.
Half of energy loss in target.
The uncertainties of the thicknesses of target
and degrader are much smaller than the uncertainty of
the total reaction cross section. Therefore, the rrror
due to the target and degrader thickness uncertainty is
not taken into account.
The number of fragments observed depends on the
efficiency of the detector used.
Besides the statistical errors of the counting rates
for the most exotic isotopes, the transmission
calculations have the highest uncertainty. In present
analysis, authors used an eror of 20% for transmission
higher than 20%, increasing to 50% for a transmission
of 10%
The errors estimated in such a way are then used to
modify the number of incident particles N(p) and the
number of observed fragments N(f), respectively. The
differences between these value and the central value
are finally added quadratically.
.See above.
.The errors for the primary-beam intensity.
